# Design Context

Before designing or building UI, read the project root context files:

- **PRODUCT.md** — register, users, purpose, brand personality, anti-references, strategic principles
- **DESIGN.md** — visual system (colors, typography, elevation, components, do's/don'ts)

These are the source of truth. Do not invent a parallel aesthetic; extend what they define.

## Quick reference

| | |
|---|---|
| **Register** | Brand-led product (guest booking first; staff management second) |
| **Users** | Guests booking rooms, plus staff managing reservations from the same website |
| **Personality** | Quiet, warm, trustworthy — hospitable, not playful or fake-luxury |
| **North star** | *The Trusted Counter* — calm guesthouse front desk; legibility before transaction |
| **Color** | Restrained: maroon accent ≤10%; tinted neutrals carry the room |
| **Type** | Single warm humanist sans; one family, multiple weights |
| **Motion** | Responsive — state transitions only; respect `prefers-reduced-motion` |
| **Reference** | Stripe-level polish and hierarchy, translated into quiet hospitality |

## Hard lines (from PRODUCT.md)

- No playful/casual travel UI, generic booking-site clichés, fake luxury gold, generic SaaS dashboards, or cold enterprise chrome
- Hospitality before hype; trust before transaction; one primary action per view
- WCAG 2.1 AA; availability, booking status, and errors never rely on color alone

